  "prompt": "Why does shaking a soda cause it to explode?",
  "response": "When you shake a soda, you're causing the dissolved carbon dioxide (CO2) gas in the liquid to form bubbles and become agitated. Here's what happens:\n\n1. Carbonated drinks contain CO2 dissolved under pressure\n\n2. Shaking causes these gas bubbles to break up and mix throughout the liquid\n\n3. The bubbles become nucleation sites (points where more bubbles can form)\n\n4. When you open the can or bottle, the sudden pressure release allows these bubbles to rapidly expand\n\n5. The bubbles quickly rise and carry liquid with them, causing the \"explosion\" or forceful spray\n\nThe more you shake the drink, the more agitated the CO2 becomes, and the more likely it is to create a dramatic spray when opened. Letting the drink settle for a few minutes before opening allows the bubbles to reform and reduces the likelihood of a messy eruption.",
